<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Geometric Sequences and Sums</h1>=20


<h2>Sequence</h2>=20

<p>A Sequence is a set of things (usually numbers) that are in order.</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/s=
equence.svg" alt=3D"Sequence" height=3D"168" width=3D"422"></p>=20


<h2>Geometric Sequences</h2>=20

<p>In a <b>Geometric Sequence</b> each term is found by <b>multiplying</b> =
the previous term by a <b>constant</b>.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, ...</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center">This sequence has a factor of 2 between each number.</=
p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">Each term (except the first term) is found by <b>multi=
plying</b> the previous term by <b>2</b>.</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
geometric-sequence-2.svg" alt=3D"geometric sequence 1,2,4,8,16," height=3D"=
85" width=3D"395"></p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p><b>In General</b> we write a Geometric Sequence like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">{a, ar, ar<sup>2</sup>, ar<sup>3</sup>, ... }</p>=
=20
<p>where:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>a</b> is the first term, and</li>=20
	<li><b>r</b> is the factor between the terms (called the <b>"common ratio"=
</b>)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: {1,2,4,8,...}</h3>=20

	<p>The sequence starts at 1 and doubles each time, so</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><b>a=3D1</b> (the first term)</li>=20
		<li><b>r=3D2</b> (the "common ratio" between terms is a doubling)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>And we get:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><span class=3D"larger">{a, ar, ar<sup>2</sup>, =
ar<sup>3</sup>, ... }</span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">=3D {1, 1=C3=972, 1=C3=972<sup>2</sup>, 1=C3=97=
2<sup>3</sup>, ... }</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">=3D {1, 2, 4, 8, ... }</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p>Note: when <span class=3D"large">r=3D0</span> the sequence becomes very =
simple:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>The first term is a</li>=20
	<li>Every term after that is 0, because we keep multiplying by zero</li>=
=20
	<li>Sequence: {a, 0, 0, 0, ...}</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>


<h2>The Rule</h2>=20

<p>We can also calculate <b>any term</b> using the Rule:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"large">x<sub>n</sub> =3D ar<sup>(n-1)</s=
up></span></p>=20
<p class=3D"center">(We use "n-1" because <span class=3D"large">ar<sup>0</s=
up></span> is for the 1st term)</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 10, 30, 90, 270, 810, 2430, ...</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center">This sequence has a factor of 3 between each number.</=
p>=20
	<p>The values of <b>a</b> and <b>r</b> are:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><b>a =3D 10</b> (the first term)</li>=20
		<li><b>r =3D 3</b> (the "common ratio")</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>The Rule for any term is:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">x<sub>n</sub> =3D 10 =C3=97 3<sup>(n-1)</sup></=
p>=20
	<p>So, the <b>4th</b> term is:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"two">=20
	<div class=3D"larger">x<sub>4</sub></div>

<div class=3D"rtlt">=3D 10 =C3=97 3<sup>(4-1)</sup></div>

<div class=3D"lt"></div>

<div class=3D"rtlt">=3D 10 =C3=97 3<sup>3</sup></div>

<div class=3D"lt"></div>

<div class=3D"rtlt">=3D 10 =C3=97 27</div>

<div class=3D"lt"></div>

<div class=3D"rtlt">=3D 270</div>
</div>=20

<p>Likewise the <b>10th</b> term is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large"><span class=3D"larger">x<sub>10 </sub></span> =3D=
 10 =C3=97 3<sup>(10-1)</sup> =3D 10 =C3=97 3<sup>9</sup> =3D 10 =C3=97 196=
83 =3D 196830</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>A Geometric Sequence can also have <b>smaller and smaller</b> values:</p=
>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 4, 2, 1, 0,5, 0,25, ...</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center">This sequence has a factor of 0,5 (a half) between eac=
h number.<br></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">Its Rule is <b>x<sub>n</sub> =3D 4 =C3=97 (0,5)<sup>n-=
1</sup></b></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Why "Geometric" Sequence?</h2>=20

<p>Because it is like increasing the dimensions in <b>geometry</b>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/image=
s/geometric-sequence.gif" alt=3D"Geometric Sequence" height=3D"217" width=
=3D"72"></div>
<div class=3D"large" style=3D"height: 60px;">a line is 1-dimensional and ha=
s a length of <span class=3D"large">r</span></div>
<div class=3D"large" style=3D"height: 60px;">in 2 dimensions a square has a=
n area of <span class=3D"large">r<sup>2</sup></span></div>
<div class=3D"large" style=3D"height: 60px;">in 3 dimensions a cube has vol=
ume <span class=3D"large">r<sup>3</sup></span></div>
<div class=3D"large" style=3D"height: 60px;">and so on (yes we can have 4 a=
nd more dimensions in mathematics).</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>Geometric Sequences are sometimes called Geometric Progressions (G.P.=E2=
=80=99s)</p>=20
</div>


<h2>Summing a Geometric Series</h2>=20

<p><b>To sum these:</b></p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">a + ar + ar<sup>2</sup> + ... + ar<sup>(n-1)</su=
p></p>=20
<p class=3D"center">(Each term is <span class=3D"large">ar<sup>k</sup></spa=
n>, where k starts at 0 and goes up to n-1)</p>=20
<p><b>We can use this handy formula:</b></p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">=20
<div class=3D"sigma">=20
<div class=3D"to">n=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(ar<sup>k</sup>) =3D a<span class=3D"tall">(</spa=
n> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 r<sup>n</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 r</e=
m> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20

<p class=3D"center"><b>a</b> is the first term<br>
<b>r</b> is the <b>"common ratio"</b> between terms<br>
<b>n</b> is the number of terms</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p><i>What is that funny =CE=A3 symbol?</i> It is called <a href=3D"https:/=
/www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/sigma-notation.html">Sigma Notation</a></p>=20
<div class=3D"center"><span class=3D"times" style=3D"font-size:300%; vertic=
al-align: middle;">=CE=A3</span> (called Sigma) means "sum up"
</div>
<p>And below and above it are shown the starting and ending values:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/s=
igma-notation.svg" alt=3D"Sigma Notation" height=3D"118" width=3D"451"></p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center">It says "Sum up <i><b>n</b></i> where <i><b>n</b></i> g=
oes from 1 to 4. Answer=3D<b>10</b></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>The formula is easy to use ... just "plug in" the values of <b>a</b>, <b=
>r</b> and <b>n</b></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Sum the first 4 terms of 10, 30, 90, 270, 810, 2430, ...</h3>=
=20

	<p class=3D"center">This sequence has a factor of 3 between each number.</=
p>=20
	<p>The values of <b>a</b>, <b>r</b> and <b>n</b> are:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><b>a =3D 10</b> (the first term)</li>=20
		<li><b>r =3D 3</b> (the "common ratio")</li>=20
		<li><b>n =3D 4</b> (we want to sum the first 4 terms)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"center large">=20
	<div class=3D"sigma">=20
	<div class=3D"to">n=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(ar<sup>k</sup>) =3D a<span class=3D"tall">(</spa=
n> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 r<sup>n</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 r</e=
m> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20

<p>Becomes:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">=20
<div class=3D"sigma">=20
<div class=3D"to">4=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(10=C3=973<sup>k</sup>) =3D 10<span class=3D"tall=
">(</span> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 3<sup>4</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=
=92 3</em> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span> =3D 400</div>

</div>=20

<p>You can check it yourself:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">10 + 30 + 90 + 270 =3D 400</p>=20
<p>And, yes, it is easier to just add them <i>in this example</i>, as there=
 are only 4 terms.</p>=20
<p>But imagine adding 50 terms ... then the formula is much easier.</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Using the Formula</h2>=20

<p>Let's see the formula in action:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Grains of Rice on a Chess Board</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"floatRt"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/games/chess.htm=
l"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/chess-board.gif" alt=3D"ch=
ess board" height=3D"149" width=3D"150"></a></p>=20
	<p>On the page <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/binary-digits.html">B=
inary Digits</a> we give an example of grains of rice on a chess board. The=
 question is asked:</p>=20
	<p>When we place rice on a chess board:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>1 grain on the first square,</li>=20
		<li>2 grains on the second square,</li>=20
		<li>4 grains on the third and so on,</li>=20
		<li>...</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p class=3D"center">... <b>doubling</b> the grains of rice on each square =
...</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><b>... how many grains of rice in total?</b></p>=20
	<p>So we have:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><b>a =3D 1</b> (the first term)</li>=20
		<li><b>r =3D 2</b> (doubles each time)</li>=20
		<li><b>n =3D 64</b> (64 squares on a chess board)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"center large">=20
	<div class=3D"sigma">=20
	<div class=3D"to">n=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(ar<sup>k</sup>) =3D a<span class=3D"tall">(</spa=
n> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 r<sup>n</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 r</e=
m> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20

<p>Becomes:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">=20
<div class=3D"sigma">=20
<div class=3D"to">64=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(1=C3=972<sup>k</sup>) =3D 1<span class=3D"tall">=
(</span> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 2<sup>64</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=
=92 2</em> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>
</div>=20

<p class=3D"center large">=3D <span class=3D"f"><u>1 =E2=88=92 2<sup>64</su=
p></u><em>=E2=88=921</em></span></p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">=3D 2<sup>64</sup> =E2=88=92 1</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">=3D 18.446.744.073.709.551.615</p>=20
<p>Which was exactly the result we got on the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsi=
sfun.com/binary-digits.html">Binary Digits</a> page (thank goodness!)</p>=
=20
</div>=20

<p>And another example, this time with <b>r</b> less than 1:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Add up the first 10 terms of the Geometric Sequence that halv=
es each time:</h3>=20

	<h3 class=3D"center">{ 1/2, 1/4, 1/8, 1/16, ... }</h3>=20

	<p>The values of <b>a</b>, <b>r</b> and <b>n</b> are:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><b>a =3D =C2=BD</b> (the first term)</li>=20
		<li><b>r =3D =C2=BD</b> (halves each time)</li>=20
		<li><b>n =3D 10</b> (10 terms to add)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"center large">=20
	<div class=3D"sigma">=20
	<div class=3D"to">n=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(ar<sup>k</sup>) =3D a<span class=3D"tall">(</spa=
n> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 r<sup>n</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 r</e=
m> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20

<p>Becomes:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/p=
artial-sum-i2.gif" alt=3D"Sigma" class=3D"imgBg" height=3D"180" width=3D"23=
9"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">Very close to 1.</p>=20
<p><i>(Question: if we continue to increase <span class=3D"large">n</span>,=
 what happens?)</i></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Why Does the Formula Work?</h2>=20

<p>Let's see <b>why</b> the formula works, because we get to use an interes=
ting "trick" which is worth knowing.</p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt"><b>First</b>, call the whole sum <b>=
"S"</b>:</span><span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"large">&nbsp;&nbsp;S&nbsp;=
=3D a + ar + ar<sup>2</sup> + ... + ar<sup>(n=E2=88=922)</sup></span><span =
class=3D"large">+ ar<sup>(n=E2=88=921)</sup></span></span> <span class=3D"l=
t"><b>Next</b>, multiply <b>S</b> by <b>r</b>:</span><span class=3D"rt"><sp=
an class=3D"large">S=C2=B7r&nbsp;=3D ar + ar<sup>2</sup> + ar<sup>3</sup> +=
 ... + ar<sup>(n=E2=88=921)</sup> + ar<sup>n</sup></span></span></div>
<p class=3D"center large">Notice that <span class=3D"larger">S</span> and <=
span class=3D"larger">S=C2=B7r</span> are similar?</p>=20
<p class=3D"large">Now <b>subtract</b> them!</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/g=
eometric-sum-proof.svg" alt=3D"Proof" height=3D"92" width=3D"400"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><b>Wow! All the terms in the middle neatly cancel out.<=
/b><br>
(Which is a neat trick)</p>=20
<p>By subtracting <span class=3D"large">S=C2=B7r</span> from <span class=3D=
"large">S</span> we get a simple result:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p class=3D"center large">S =E2=88=92 S=C2=B7r =3D a =E2=88=92 ar<sup>n</su=
p></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Let's rearrange it to find <span class=3D"large">S</span>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Factor out <b>S</b> and <b>a</b>:</s=
pan><span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"larger">S(1=E2=88=92r) =3D a(1=E2=88=
=92r<sup>n</sup>)</span></span> <span class=3D"lt">Divide by <b>(1=E2=88=92=
r)</b>:</span><span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"larger">S =3D a <span class=
=3D"f"><u>(1=E2=88=92r<sup>n</sup>)</u><em>(1=E2=88=92r)</em></span></span>=
</span></div>
<p>Which is our formula (ta-da!):</p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">=20
<div class=3D"sigma">=20
<div class=3D"to">n=E2=88=921</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(ar<sup>k</sup>) =3D a<span class=3D"tall">(</spa=
n> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1 =E2=88=92 r<sup>n</sup></u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 r</e=
m> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20


<h2>Infinite Geometric Series</h2>=20

<p>So what happens when <span class=3D"large">n</span> goes to <b>infinity<=
/b>?</p>=20
<p>We can use this formula:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">=20
<div class=3D"sigma">=20
<div class=3D"to">=E2=88=9E</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(ar<sup>k</sup>) =3D a<span class=3D"tall">(</spa=
n> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1</u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 r</em> </span> <span class=
=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20

<p>But <b>be careful</b>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><b>r</b> must be between (but not including) <b>=
=E2=88=921 and 1</b></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>So our infnite geometric series has a <b>finite sum</b> when the ratio i=
s less than 1 (and greater than =E2=88=921)</p>=20
<p>Let's bring back our previous example, and see what happens:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Add up ALL the terms of the Geometric Sequence that halves ea=
ch time:</h3>=20

	<h3 class=3D"center">{ <span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>2</em></span>, <span =
class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>4</em></span>, <span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>8</em>=
</span>, <span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>16</em></span>, ... }</h3>=20

	<p>We have:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><b>a =3D =C2=BD</b> (the first term)</li>=20
		<li><b>r =3D =C2=BD</b> (halves each time)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>And so:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"center large">=20
	<div class=3D"sigma">=20
	<div class=3D"to">=E2=88=9E</div>
<div class=3D"symb">=CE=A3</div>
<div class=3D"from">k=3D0</div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"sigma-text">(=C2=BD =C3=97 =C2=BD<sup>k</sup>) =3D =C2=BD<spa=
n class=3D"tall">(</span> <span class=3D"f"> <u>1</u> <em>1 =E2=88=92 =C2=
=BD</em> </span> <span class=3D"tall">)</span></div>

</div>=20

<p class=3D"center large">=3D <span class=3D"f"><u>=C2=BD =C3=97 1</u><em>=
=C2=BD</em></span> =3D 1</p>=20
<p>Yes, adding <b><span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>2</em></span> + <span class=
=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>4</em></span> + <span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>8</em></sp=
an> + ...</b> and so on equals <b>exactly 1</b>.</p>=20
</div>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=20

<p>Don't believe me? Just look at this square:</p>=20
<p>By adding up <b><span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>2</em></span> + <span clas=
s=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>4</em></span> + <span class=3D"f"><u>1</u><em>8</em></s=
pan> + ...</b></p>=20
<p>we end up with the whole thing!</p></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebr=
a/images/infinite-series-1-2n.svg" alt=3D"Sum of 1/2^n as boxes" height=3D"=
208" width=3D"208"></span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20


<h2>Recurring Decimal</h2>=20

<p>On another page we asked <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/9recurrin=
g.html">"Does 0,999... equal 1?"</a>, well, let us see if we can calculate =
it:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Calculate 0,999...</h3>=20

	<p>We can write a recurring decimal as a sum like this:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
geometric-infinite-sum-d.gif" alt=3D"Sigma" class=3D"imgBg" height=3D"120" =
width=3D"398"></p>=20
	<p>And now we can use the formula:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
geometric-infinite-sum-e.gif" alt=3D"Sigma" class=3D"imgBg" height=3D"54" w=
idth=3D"403"></p>=20
	<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>Yes! 0,999... <i><b>does</b></i> equal 1.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>So there we have it ... Geometric Sequences (and their sums) can do all =
sorts of amazing and powerful things.</p>=20
